description.value: Circular, silver-gilt basin which is embossed, chased and engraved. At the centre, the raised boss terminates in a ring of rounded 'claws', five or six of which are broken, while the remainder are no longer being used (as intended) to grip the armorial medallion set on the boss. This roundel is engraved with a coat-of-arms: gules, a cross or, on a shield; the supporters, greyhounds rampant, argent and collared; above the mantling and crowned helm, a crest: a greyhound sejant, collared. Below the ring of 'claws' are a moulding with a pounced surface interrupted by a diagonal ribbon (repeated six times, at evenly spaced points of the circle), and a narrow concentric band of a debased form of egg-and-dart motif. The broad zone of ornament within this central raised area is a finely chased palmette and foliate repetitive design. It is enclosed by a raised laurel-wreath, which is separated by a plain zone from the quasi-architectural arcade of the broad, concave area of the basin. This band of decoration can be seen as a series of round-headed recessed niches (or deep lobes) between which is a broad 'pilaster', alternately decorated with three vertical raised flutes (or ribs) surmounted by a spiralling fleurette and a guilloche pattern surmounted by an equally large single rosette. The inner 'base' of the arcade is unified by the introduction of a repetitive pattern of two alternating pendentive motifs chased and silhouetted against a pounced background.  The broad, flat border of the basin is divided by six equidistantly arranged oval cartouches containing biblical  scenes, five Plagues of Egypt and, lastly, the destruction of Pharaoh's army in the Red Sea:  (i) ‘The plague of frogs’ (Exodus 8, vv. 2-14). An interior scene, the walls covered with looped hangings ornamented with a delicate pattern executed in a pointillé technique; at a circular table, with legs in the form of satyr legs and covered by a fringed cloth delicately decorated with a lozenge pattern, are seated the frightened figures of the crowned and bearded Pharaoh and his crowned consort; a servitor, entering from the right, carries a large jug in his left hand and a covered cup. The agitated Pharaoh, in Roman-style military dress, and his consort gesticulate towards the frogs advancing from all directions, four having leapt on to the table itself.  (ii) ‘The plague of boils and blains’ (Exodus 9, vv. 8-12). On the left of the scene, the crowned figure of the bearded Pharaoh in Roman-style military costume is depicted recoiling in horror as he sits on his raised throne beneath a baldacchino with the curtains looped back; in front of him stand Moses and Aaron - the latter wearing a bishop's mitre and holding a staff; to the right, two stricken Egyptians and two cattle are stretched out on the ground.  (iii) ‘The firstborn of Egypt slain’ (Exodus 12, vv. 29-30). description.value: Silver-gilt ewer richly embossed and chased that the upper part of the neck and a small section of the handle are virtually the only surfaces that have been left plain. The essentially classical form comprises an oviform body on a short, narrow stem and a relatively small foot, with a high spout and handle, the latter rising up in a steep u-curve above the neck-rim. However, the decorative detail is entirely drawn from the repertoire of Mannerist art and transforms the ewer into a sculptural masterpiece of Antwerp Mannerism.  The two principal subjects are Neptune and Amphitrite, executed in low relief, each contained within a roundel (DIAM. 6.2 cm) in the middle of either side of the ewer. Both are represented riding a sea-monster across the waves with windblown drapery behind them and blowing a large conch shell (or marine trumpet) held in one hand. The bearded and dishevelled Neptune holds in his raised left hand his trident, which points vertically downwards and rests on the ferocious, ugly head of the monster he sits astride. Neptune's cloak, fastened by a brooch at the neck, billows out behind him to the right, leaving his torso naked, though his thighs and legs are covered in drapery that merges into the waves. The sinuous body and tail of the monster curve away to the left. By contrast, Amphitrite is depicted fully clad in classical-style drapery; she is shown sitting sideways on an equally fearsome monster through whose open jaws are passed the lightest of thin reins that loop up over her right shoulder. Amphitrite's right hand is raised as if to smooth her immaculate coiffure. The remainder of the body of the ewer is covered in elaborate strapwork, filled with terms, masks, grotesques, snails, snakes and restless foliage. The simple strapwork frames of the two roundels are linked by a broad horizontal strapwork band, dividing the body of the ewer into a broad upper zone and the much larger lower zone. In the upper zone, above the Amphitrite roundel, there are, facing each other, a pair of long-necked, female-headed, sphinxes or animal grotesques with long, dragon-like tails and scaly bodies with spiky spines; in between them, a horned goat (?) mask is in high relief on a strapwork cartouche, behind which squats a winged figure, whose head, legs and arms emerge and whose hands grasp the spiralling sprays of foliage. description.value: Circular basin, silver-gilt. Richly embossed and chased. Central boss engraved with coat-of-arms of Counts of Aspremont-Lynden, surrounded by chased palmette and foliate design and enclosed by a raised laurel-wreath. Concave area of basin has series of recessed lobes between alternate decorated raised flutes, surmounted by large single rosettes. Border divided by six equidistant oval cartouches containing biblical scenes, five Plagues of Egypt and the destruction of Pharaoh's army in the Red Sea. Between each cartouche a strapwork 'basket' is filled with fruit and foliage and on either side a large satyr, Pan-figure or nymph holds a ribbon from which more fruit, flowers, corn and foliage are suspended. Moulded rim with narrow ornamental band decorated with repetitive pattern of dots and dashes. Marked.
